"Boo K.-O., Kwon W.-T., Oh J.-H., Baek H.-J.","Response of global warming on regional climate change over Korea: An experiment with the MM5 model",2004,"Geophysical Research Letters","31","21",,"L21206 1","4",,,10.1029/2004GL021171,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-13244255623&partnerID=40&md5=0af60579ba526e100be21c475a1af0e7","Climate Research Laboratory, Meteorological Research Institute, Korea Meteorological Administration, Seoul 156-720, South Korea; Dept. of Environ. Atmospheric Sci., Pukyong National University, Pusan 608-737, South Korea","Boo, K.-O., Climate Research Laboratory, Meteorological Research Institute, Korea Meteorological Administration, Seoul 156-720, South Korea; Kwon, W.-T., Climate Research Laboratory, Meteorological Research Institute, Korea Meteorological Administration, Seoul 156-720, South Korea; Oh, J.-H., Dept. of Environ. Atmospheric Sci., Pukyong National University, Pusan 608-737, South Korea; Baek, H.-J., Climate Research Laboratory, Meteorological Research Institute, Korea Meteorological Administration, Seoul 156-720, South Korea","This study is to investigate changes in regional surface climate arising from global warming with MM5 downscaling simulation for the period 1971-2100. The main focus is on the drought conditions over Korea. Palmer Drought Severity Index (PDSI) is utilized as a measure of drought severity. The important findings show the increase of surface air temperature by 6°C and precipitation by 25% over Korea at the end of the 21st century. The increasing trend of temperature is associated with an increasing trend of evapotranspiration and precipitation. Climatological precipitation amount appropriate for existing conditions is larger than the precipitation amounts. Hence, it actually produces deficit in precipitation. This exhibits a negative PDSI. As a result droughts are expected to be severe and frequent. Better resolved topography in MM5 induces large changes in local precipitation compared with temperature. Consequently peaks of negative PDSI anomalies appear over southern parts of Korea, where a large reduction in precipitation is noticed in addition to warming. Copyright 2004 by the American Geophysical Union.","1610 Global Change: Atmosphere (0315, 0325); 1812 Hydrology: Drought; 3309 Meteorology and Atmospheric Dynamics: Climatology (1620)","Climatology; Computer simulation; Drought; Evapotranspiration; Mathematical models; Precipitation (meteorology); Reduction; Surfaces; Palmer drought severity index (PDSI); Regional surface climate; Surface air temperature; Topography; Climate change; climate change; climate modeling; global warming; regional climate; Asia; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Far East; Korea; World",,,,,,"Alley, W.M., The Palmer Drought Severity Index: Limitations and assumptions (1984) J. Clim. Appl. Meteorol., 23, pp. 1100-1109; Choi, Y.-J., Kim, H.-M., Cho, H.-M., Calculation of the Palmer Drought Severity Index and analysis of temporal and spacial characteristics of drought in Korea (1994) J. Atmos. Res., 11, pp. 67-76; Dai, A., Trenberth, K.E., Karl, T.R., Global variations in droughts and wet spells: 1900-1995 (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 25, pp. 3367-3370; Easterling, D.R., Evans, J.L., Groisman, P.Y., Karl, T.R., Kunkel, K.E., Ambenje, P., Observed yariability and trends in extreme climate events: A brief review (2000) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 81, pp. 417-426; Giorgi, F., Brodeur, C.S., Bates, G.T., Regional climate change scenarios over the United States produced with a nested regional climate model (1994) J. Clim., 7, pp. 375-399; Hewitson, B.C., Crane, R.G., Climate downscaling: Techniques and application (1996) Clim. Res., 7, pp. 85-95; Hong, S.-Y., Juang, H.-M., Orography blending in the lateral boundary of a regional model (1998) Mon. Weather Rev., 126, pp. 1714-1718; Hu, Q., Willson, G.D., Effects of temperature anomalies on the Palmer Drought Severity Index in the central United States (2000) Int. J. Climatol., 20, pp. 1